WEBVTT

01:24.376 --> 01:25.711
Your Grace.

01:59.703 --> 02:01.705
(INDISTINCT CHATTER)

02:09.253 --> 02:12.466
Sergeant, I'm here on behalf
of the Red Cross

02:12.633 --> 02:14.426
and I'd like to speak
with General Kitchener.

02:14.593 --> 02:16.261
There is
no General Kitchener here.

02:16.428 --> 02:18.889
Your Grace? Your Grace?
Let... Let him in.

02:20.682 --> 02:22.559
Well, if Morton's here, then
Kitchener can't be far away.

02:22.726 --> 02:24.645
My apologies, Your Grace.

02:24.728 --> 02:26.104
Security's paramount right now.

02:26.271 --> 02:28.315
It's a secret that you're
visiting with the general.

02:28.482 --> 02:30.275
We can't be too careful
with these Boers

02:30.359 --> 02:31.610
and their guerilla tactics.

02:31.777 --> 02:32.819
Too careful?

02:32.986 --> 02:35.489
Looks like this place
could use a lot more care.

02:35.656 --> 02:38.116
Begging your pardon, sir,
but these concentration camps

02:38.200 --> 02:39.451
are the reason we're winning this war.

02:39.743 --> 02:40.744
This way.

02:44.957 --> 02:49.336
Orlando. Our knight in shining armor.

02:50.003 --> 02:51.338
Thank you for coming.

02:51.880 --> 02:53.423
What's going on, Kitchener?

02:54.091 --> 02:55.676
It seems that you've been

02:55.759 --> 02:56.927
somewhat liberal with the truth.

02:57.094 --> 02:59.304
Time has not been kind here.

02:59.471 --> 03:01.181
Well, you'll have to explain that
to Emily.

03:01.348 --> 03:03.934
On my return to England,
it will be my first port of call.

03:04.101 --> 03:05.269
She's outside,

03:05.435 --> 03:07.145
<i>with Conrad.</i>

03:07.855 --> 03:09.982
Why are we here, Mother?

03:11.191 --> 03:13.443
Do you remember why
King Arthur and his knights

03:13.527 --> 03:14.987
had a round table?

03:16.697 --> 03:19.116
Because it meant
that all men were equal.

03:20.075 --> 03:22.369
It's important that people
born into privilege

03:22.452 --> 03:23.871
lead by example.

03:24.037 --> 03:27.124
That's why your father and I
are patrons of the Red Cross.

03:28.208 --> 03:29.501
Helping others,

03:29.668 --> 03:32.337
not hiding behind our status.

03:36.967 --> 03:38.802
Never forget that.

03:39.386 --> 03:40.470
Hmm?

03:43.557 --> 03:45.767
I'm just going to check
on your father.

03:49.062 --> 03:50.480
Stay here, Conrad.

03:55.068 --> 03:58.488
This terrible war would be over, Shola,

03:59.198 --> 04:02.784
if King Arthur and his
noble knights were still here.

04:02.868 --> 04:06.330
(CHUCKLES) Of course.
And which one would you be?

04:06.747 --> 04:08.665
I'd be Lancelot.

04:09.124 --> 04:11.793
Father would be Arthur.
Mother, Guinevere.

04:12.294 --> 04:15.088
And you, the mighty Merlin.

04:15.172 --> 04:16.173
Really?

04:17.466 --> 04:20.636
EMILY: This is ridiculous.
We're wasting precious time.

04:20.802 --> 04:22.804
Look around, people are dying.

04:22.971 --> 04:24.973
We have emergency supplies
from the Red Cross.

04:25.140 --> 04:26.683
Thank God she's on our side.

04:26.850 --> 04:28.268
Well, on my side, at least.

04:28.435 --> 04:29.478
KITCHENER: She's more of a force

04:29.561 --> 04:30.771
than any of our enemies.
(CHUCKLES)

04:30.854 --> 04:32.231
There's General Kitchener.

04:32.397 --> 04:35.817
Well, open the gates!
Bring in those supplies!

04:36.193 --> 04:37.444
Emily!

04:37.736 --> 04:39.571
-(GUNSHOT)
-(GROANS)

04:41.240 --> 04:43.242
(PEOPLE CLAMORING)

04:44.034 --> 04:45.619
Lie down until I get back.

04:46.453 --> 04:47.704
(GUNS FIRING)

04:58.340 --> 04:59.550
Go back to Conrad.

05:05.931 --> 05:07.140
Go to hell, Kitchener.

05:08.350 --> 05:09.685
(YELLING)

05:12.563 --> 05:15.315
SHOLA: I got him! Stop fire!

05:19.736 --> 05:22.281
Emily!

05:22.948 --> 05:25.075
SOLDIER: Cease fire!

05:25.158 --> 05:26.493
(FIRING STOPS)

05:26.577 --> 05:27.661
(GROANS)

05:28.954 --> 05:29.955
Emily.

05:31.081 --> 05:32.833
Darling, I'm here.

05:36.753 --> 05:39.256
I'm here. Darling, I'm here.

05:40.757 --> 05:43.051
That's it. I'm here.
You have to stay with me.

05:43.802 --> 05:45.345
You have to stay with me.

05:45.512 --> 05:46.555
Darling?

05:49.099 --> 05:51.018
Protect our son.

05:52.895 --> 05:56.648
Protect him from this world. And...

05:57.691 --> 06:00.110
Never let him see war again.

06:07.201 --> 06:09.077
Promise me.

06:10.621 --> 06:11.872
I promise.

07:27.656 --> 07:29.491
(ENGINE WHIRRING)

07:51.638 --> 07:53.265
-You know, Conrad...
-Hmm?

07:53.348 --> 07:56.185
...up there, I feel free.

07:56.351 --> 07:59.897
Yes, I'm very much looking forward
to my first solo flight.

08:00.063 --> 08:02.232
Remember what happened
to Icarus, Conrad,

08:02.399 --> 08:04.484
when he flew too close to the sun.

08:05.194 --> 08:07.779
Well, I remember him
needing to escape, no?

08:07.946 --> 08:09.990
(LAUGHING)
Well, he got burned.

08:10.741 --> 08:12.784
I think we both see
that story differently.

08:12.951 --> 08:15.037
-Welcome home, Your Grace.
-Thank you, Shola.

08:16.246 --> 08:19.416
-Afternoon, everyone.
-ALL: Afternoon, Your Grace.

08:20.083 --> 08:21.543
Ready for your maiden flight yet, Shola?

08:21.710 --> 08:23.795
Well, if God wanted man to fly,

08:23.879 --> 08:25.214
he would have given him wings.

08:25.547 --> 08:28.300
Yes, I suppose.
You drive Father's car?

08:28.383 --> 08:29.676
SHOLA: Mmm-hmm.

08:30.511 --> 08:31.887
You haven't any wheels.

08:44.274 --> 08:45.275
Nanny Watkins.

08:47.861 --> 08:49.655
My study in five minutes.

08:52.658 --> 08:54.618
Your Grace.

09:05.379 --> 09:06.421
Your Grace.

09:06.588 --> 09:09.424
I should be reprimanding you
for your insolence.

09:10.217 --> 09:12.469
Your opinion behind closed doors
is one thing, Polly,

09:12.636 --> 09:14.847
but I will not tolerate
such demonstrations

09:14.930 --> 09:16.139
in front of my household.

09:16.682 --> 09:19.476
I'll play by your rules
when you play by mine.

09:19.893 --> 09:22.145
Do you really think
you can keep secrets from me?

09:22.688 --> 09:23.730
What do you mean?

09:23.897 --> 09:26.817
Once again, you've turned down
Cousin Felix's invitation

09:26.900 --> 09:28.861
for Conrad to stay
with him in Russia.

09:29.653 --> 09:30.904
And how do you know that?

09:31.488 --> 09:33.490
Us nannies love a good gossip.

09:33.657 --> 09:34.950
And we've all noticed

09:35.033 --> 09:37.452
that you've no problem
with Felix traveling here,

09:37.619 --> 09:40.247
but you seem to have a problem
with Conrad traveling there.

09:40.414 --> 09:42.082
Or anywhere, for that matter.

09:42.749 --> 09:46.336
Yeah. Guilty as charged.
Well, I'm sorry.

09:46.503 --> 09:48.172
I should have
discussed it with you.

09:48.630 --> 09:50.799
Has all this
flying around in circles

09:50.883 --> 09:51.967
made you forget your manners?

09:52.426 --> 09:53.552
Well, what have I done now?

09:53.719 --> 09:55.304
You haven't even offered me a drink.

09:55.596 --> 09:57.264
Oh, yes, I'm sorry.

09:58.056 --> 10:00.642
And if we had discussed this,

10:00.726 --> 10:02.853
what would my opinion have been?

10:03.478 --> 10:05.606
You think that my

10:05.772 --> 10:08.567
fear for Conrad's safety
is a weakness.

10:09.026 --> 10:10.527
Fear is natural.

10:11.278 --> 10:13.155
The problem is,
the more you fear something,

10:13.238 --> 10:15.115
the more likely it is to come true.

10:15.991 --> 10:20.037
Hmm. So, then,
we're both in need of a nanny.

10:20.412 --> 10:22.414
So it would seem.

10:29.922 --> 10:31.173
(SHOLA YELLS)

10:31.256 --> 10:32.758
(BOTH GRUNTING)

10:36.678 --> 10:37.679
Higher!

10:45.604 --> 10:47.481
Can you fight with only one arm?

10:47.648 --> 10:49.274
Oh, yes.

10:49.566 --> 10:51.860
If I had someone left to fight.

10:55.364 --> 10:56.615
(GUNSHOT)

10:57.407 --> 11:00.410
Shola. Do you really think
a knife can beat a bullet?

11:00.869 --> 11:03.205
This is how people
are fighting nowadays.

11:03.372 --> 11:04.665
Now, clean yourselves up

11:04.748 --> 11:07.376
before this afternoon's appointment.

11:23.767 --> 11:26.854
My father also brought me here
for my first suit.

11:27.354 --> 11:30.440
Kingsman, world's finest tailor.

11:31.733 --> 11:33.151
(BELL DINGING)

11:38.073 --> 11:40.117
-Morning.
-Your Grace.

11:40.284 --> 11:42.327
Fitting room number one
is ready for you.

11:42.661 --> 11:43.996
Thank you.

11:46.498 --> 11:48.292
Well, here we are.

11:49.918 --> 11:51.962
<i>I wish your mother could see you now.</i>

11:52.504 --> 11:54.590
She would've been so proud.

11:55.716 --> 11:57.426
I hope so, Father.

11:59.720 --> 12:03.515
Although, I might get more use
out of a shooting suit or

12:03.682 --> 12:06.059
a smoking jacket, you know.

12:06.226 --> 12:09.479
Whatever might help
in the pursuit of fine birds.

12:10.230 --> 12:12.065
Oh, come on, Father.

12:12.900 --> 12:14.234
It's a big world out there.

12:14.401 --> 12:15.402
Sooner or later,

12:15.485 --> 12:17.279
you're going to have to
let me enjoy it, even if,

12:18.322 --> 12:19.865
you know,
even if you don't want to.

12:22.367 --> 12:23.452
You know,

12:23.619 --> 12:24.828
Conrad,

12:27.247 --> 12:30.417
our ancestors,
they were terrible people.

12:30.959 --> 12:34.671
They robbed, lied, pillaged,
and killed, until one day,

12:34.838 --> 12:37.216
they found themselves noblemen.

12:38.050 --> 12:39.676
But that nobility,

12:40.761 --> 12:42.846
it never came from chivalry.

12:43.764 --> 12:46.558
It came from being tough
and ruthless.

12:47.476 --> 12:51.480
Back then, to be called a "gentleman"

12:51.647 --> 12:53.524
would have been a death sentence.

12:54.399 --> 12:59.404
Not the mark of honor it is today.

12:59.780 --> 13:01.490
We are Oxfords,

13:02.241 --> 13:04.201
not rogues.

13:07.037 --> 13:08.038
KITCHENER: <i>Oxford!</i>

13:08.330 --> 13:10.666
-Kitchener.
-(LAUGHS)

13:10.749 --> 13:12.459
Well, so glad
we share the same tailor.

13:12.626 --> 13:14.586
Indeed. Well, the Kingsman clientele

13:14.670 --> 13:15.963
is enough to make any club envious.

13:16.046 --> 13:19.091
Mmm-hmm. Oxford, can I
borrow you for a moment?

13:19.591 --> 13:20.634
Is there somewhere private?

13:20.801 --> 13:22.594
May I suggest the pattern room
upstairs, sir.

13:22.761 --> 13:23.971
Perfect.

13:24.137 --> 13:26.974
Conrad, this is Morton,
my aide-de-camp.

13:27.140 --> 13:29.643
Morton, look after
young Conrad for us, will you?

13:29.810 --> 13:31.061
It will be my pleasure, my lord.

13:31.144 --> 13:32.145
Good.

13:43.073 --> 13:45.450
I gather you turned down
our Austrian friend

13:45.534 --> 13:48.620
Archduke Ferdinand's
invitation to his shoot.

13:49.454 --> 13:51.498
Surely your pacifism
doesn't extend

13:51.623 --> 13:53.458
to a few birds, does it?

13:53.625 --> 13:55.252
Us bumping into each other here

13:55.335 --> 13:57.296
was no coincidence, was it?

13:58.630 --> 14:01.258
Walls have ears
in Whitehall these days.

14:01.675 --> 14:05.137
Which is why I felt Kingsman
a safer place for a chat.

14:05.220 --> 14:06.221
OXFORD: Mmm-hmm.

14:06.305 --> 14:09.308
I'm worried that Ferdinand's
political ambitions

14:09.391 --> 14:11.185
may be putting him in danger.

14:12.603 --> 14:15.230
I need you to do me a small favor.

14:15.606 --> 14:17.149
What sort of favor?

14:17.316 --> 14:18.734
MORTON: So, you're serious
about being a soldier?

14:18.901 --> 14:20.861
-Oh, yes.
-Which regiment?

14:21.028 --> 14:22.112
Uh... Grenadiers.

14:22.196 --> 14:23.405
Grenadiers. Well,

14:23.697 --> 14:26.241
when the time comes, contact me.

14:26.325 --> 14:27.326
I'll see what I can do.

14:27.492 --> 14:28.785
OXFORD: Conrad.

14:31.580 --> 14:34.166
You're going to need
that shooting suit after all.

14:46.929 --> 14:48.764
(MACHINERY RUMBLING)

14:59.483 --> 15:01.902
(ALARMED BLEATING)

15:19.503 --> 15:20.838
My Shepherd.

15:21.672 --> 15:25.551
I have a FabergÃ© egg
made especially for you.

15:25.717 --> 15:27.511
And look inside.

15:28.720 --> 15:31.515
A little replica of Angus,

15:31.682 --> 15:33.225
your favorite goat.

15:33.392 --> 15:34.476
SHEPHERD: You're late.

15:35.644 --> 15:37.312
Take a seat.

15:39.356 --> 15:42.901
What is trust? Hmm?

15:44.027 --> 15:47.239
Trust is having confidence

15:47.406 --> 15:49.283
in the honesty of another.

15:50.325 --> 15:52.870
That will be our weapon

15:53.036 --> 15:55.956
to change the world.

15:56.164 --> 15:58.375
Who do I trust?

15:59.501 --> 16:01.044
Animals.

16:01.461 --> 16:04.214
They never let me down

16:04.381 --> 16:08.427
and they follow
my commands blindly.

16:08.886 --> 16:11.263
The question I now have is

16:11.430 --> 16:15.934
can I trust you to behave like them?

16:16.101 --> 16:18.353
Open the boxes in front of you.

16:22.149 --> 16:26.862
These rings will be the symbol
of membership to my flock.

16:27.029 --> 16:31.366
Put them on, and you will
share in our successes.

16:31.533 --> 16:32.534
But,

16:33.202 --> 16:34.494
break my trust,

16:34.661 --> 16:37.289
and inside you will find

16:37.915 --> 16:40.375
my final gift to you.

16:40.542 --> 16:42.044
MAN: A tortoise?

16:42.252 --> 16:45.422
Am I not worthy of a better animal?

16:45.589 --> 16:46.924
Rasputin, I have a bear.

16:47.007 --> 16:48.425
I will happily exchange it with you.

16:48.592 --> 16:51.887
Yes, Princip. I will be
the great bear of Russia.

16:52.054 --> 16:53.805
Take what you believe is yours.

16:54.181 --> 16:55.933
And by all means,

16:56.099 --> 16:57.976
treat our Shepherd
with the same respect you hold

16:58.143 --> 17:00.979
for that joke of a man
who calls himself your tsar.

17:01.146 --> 17:04.233
Go ahead, Rasputin, take it.

17:04.650 --> 17:06.484
-I dare you.
-(SHEPHERD CHUCKLES)

17:06.652 --> 17:08.819
Now, now, Mata and Erik.
We are

17:08.987 --> 17:10.071
a team.

17:10.239 --> 17:13.075
And Rasputin here... (CHUCKLES)

17:13.867 --> 17:17.704
...is like my beloved Angus.
(CHUCKLING)

17:17.788 --> 17:18.872
(ANGUS BLEATS)

17:18.955 --> 17:21.165
SHEPHERD: Always butting

17:22.334 --> 17:24.002
and fucking.

17:26.463 --> 17:28.048
(BLEATING)

17:28.131 --> 17:31.552
But do not mistake fondness
for weakness,

17:31.718 --> 17:35.013
you late Russian fuckstick!

17:36.014 --> 17:38.058
As everybody knows,

17:38.892 --> 17:40.519
the tortoise

17:41.812 --> 17:44.231
eventually wins the race.

17:52.447 --> 17:53.574
SHEPHERD: Now...

17:53.657 --> 17:55.492
(HAWKS, SPITS)

17:56.159 --> 18:00.747
...my spy,
or should I say my mole,

18:00.914 --> 18:03.417
in the British government

18:03.584 --> 18:07.921
informs me that Kitchener is
concerned for the safety

18:08.088 --> 18:10.174
of the Archduke Ferdinand.

18:10.966 --> 18:14.511
Princip, my wee bear.

18:14.678 --> 18:16.430
Are you ready to prove

18:16.513 --> 18:19.183
Kitchener's concerns are justified?

18:19.349 --> 18:22.144
Yes, I am, my Shepherd.
And I will not let you down.

18:22.603 --> 18:24.855
SHEPHERD: Damn fucking right.

18:25.105 --> 18:26.190
(BANGS TABLE)

18:29.318 --> 18:31.153
(RHYTHMIC BANGING)

18:59.556 --> 19:01.558
(PEOPLE CHEERING)

19:03.727 --> 19:06.063
OXFORD: Does that make sense
to you, Ferdinand?

19:06.146 --> 19:08.273
ARCHDUKE FERDINAND:
Ah, now I understand

19:08.357 --> 19:10.984
why you accepted
my shooting invitation.

19:11.151 --> 19:15.155
I didn't really believe
Kitchener's scare tactics.

19:15.322 --> 19:17.866
Harping on about
my being in danger.

19:18.033 --> 19:20.702
OXFORD: Well, only a fool ignores
a friend's warning, Ferdi.

19:20.869 --> 19:22.246
Is it really too much to ask?

19:22.412 --> 19:23.914
I think you should come back with me

19:23.997 --> 19:25.040
and hear what he has to say.

19:25.207 --> 19:28.418
Turning you down is a hard task.

19:28.585 --> 19:30.838
I will give you my decision tonight.

19:31.004 --> 19:32.005
Good.

19:51.817 --> 19:55.279
-(PEOPLE SCREAMING)
-Drive! Drive!

19:58.073 --> 19:59.199
(INDISTINCT SHOUTING)

20:08.208 --> 20:10.502
ARCHDUKE FERDINAND:
I come here on a visit of goodwill,

20:10.586 --> 20:12.087
to be greeted by bombs?

20:12.171 --> 20:13.797
(DIGNITARIES CHUCKLING)

20:14.298 --> 20:15.299
Yes. (CLEARS THROAT)

20:15.841 --> 20:17.759
(MUFFLED) It gives me
special pleasure...

20:17.926 --> 20:19.845
I... I shouldn't have
brought you here.

20:20.387 --> 20:23.307
We need to get home,
where I can protect you.

20:23.473 --> 20:24.474
What...

20:24.850 --> 20:27.144
I just protected you.
I don't need protecting.

20:27.311 --> 20:30.105
Yes, you do, Conrad. I'm sorry,

20:30.189 --> 20:31.982
but you think you know
what the world is like,

20:32.149 --> 20:33.692
but the truth is, you're just a boy

20:33.775 --> 20:36.069
who has no idea
what men are capable of.

20:36.236 --> 20:39.072
What? Watching my mother die
wasn't a good enough introduction?

20:50.209 --> 20:52.628
(LIVELY MUSIC PLAYING IN DISTANCE)

20:58.509 --> 21:00.344
(BREATHING SHAKILY)

21:08.519 --> 21:09.520
(HORN HONKS)

21:09.603 --> 21:10.646
MAN 1: Are you sure this is right?

21:10.812 --> 21:13.190
MAN 2: Just follow my orders.

21:14.024 --> 21:16.276
Take the first left.

21:29.540 --> 21:30.874
MAN 1: It's a dead end, you fool.

21:31.083 --> 21:32.584
I knew this was the wrong way.

21:33.126 --> 21:34.461
MAN 2: I meant the next left.

21:34.670 --> 21:36.255
OXFORD: Stop arguing.
We're sitting ducks here.

21:36.839 --> 21:38.465
Get this car moving now.

21:53.397 --> 21:55.232
(PEOPLE SCREAMING)

22:18.172 --> 22:20.799
Father, it's terrible
about Ferdi and Sophie.

22:22.759 --> 22:24.386
We're safe now, aren't we?

22:24.761 --> 22:26.763
Yes, but for how long?

22:27.181 --> 22:30.058
I'm beginning to understand
what Kitchener was so afraid of.

22:30.225 --> 22:31.393
Already there are rumors

22:31.476 --> 22:33.687
the Austrians
are mobilizing their army.

22:34.021 --> 22:37.274
They don't believe this assassin
acted independently.

22:37.983 --> 22:39.610
And neither do I.

22:39.776 --> 22:40.777
It's just Serbia.

22:40.861 --> 22:42.529
I mean, it's such
a small part of the world.

22:42.613 --> 22:43.614
Why do they care?

22:44.239 --> 22:48.452
Well, because small things
can grow into big problems.

22:48.827 --> 22:50.621
<i>You see, years ago,</i>

22:50.704 --> 22:52.623
<i>there were three young cousins.</i>

22:52.789 --> 22:53.999
<i>The eldest was
a real troublemaker...</i>

22:54.166 --> 22:55.167
Put my soldier back!

22:55.334 --> 22:56.585
There are no rules in war.

22:56.752 --> 22:59.087
-I'll teach you war, Wilhelm!
-(ALL GRUNTING)

22:59.171 --> 23:00.672
OXFORD: <i>Their grandmother
was Queen Victoria...</i>

23:00.756 --> 23:01.882
Nicholas. Enough!

23:02.049 --> 23:03.300
OXFORD:
<i>...who kept them in line.</i>

23:03.467 --> 23:06.970
<i>They grew up to become
Kaiser Wilhelm of Germany,</i>

23:07.137 --> 23:10.599
<i>Tsar Nicholas of Russia,
and King George of England.</i>

23:10.682 --> 23:11.683
(LAUGHING)

23:11.767 --> 23:13.644
OXFORD: <i>And now,
poor Ferdinand's assassination</i>

23:13.727 --> 23:15.687
<i>has given the moronic kaiser</i>

23:15.854 --> 23:19.358
<i>a reason to reignite
their childhood feud.</i>

23:21.443 --> 23:24.363
But surely they've matured
enough to avoid a war?

23:24.530 --> 23:26.240
One would hope so.

23:26.573 --> 23:29.159
<i>And, thankfully,
we have our own King George</i>

23:29.243 --> 23:31.203
<i>to help keep the peace.</i>

23:33.705 --> 23:35.666
Ah. There it is.

23:42.840 --> 23:44.049
Look at us.

23:45.592 --> 23:46.927
Three young cousins

23:47.010 --> 23:49.221
who thought they knew how to rule.

23:49.388 --> 23:51.515
But now the soldiers are real.

23:52.724 --> 23:54.476
Get two copies
of this photograph made

23:54.560 --> 23:56.562
and have them delivered
with these letters immediately.

23:56.728 --> 23:58.605
I'll have Morton see to it personally.

23:58.772 --> 23:59.898
Excellent.

24:00.065 --> 24:01.441
Your Majesty.

24:05.487 --> 24:07.030
(SWEARS IN GERMAN)

24:07.114 --> 24:08.991
-(IN ENGLISH) Erik.
-My kaiser.

24:09.157 --> 24:13.161
"Restraint is a virtue.
Remember your duty."

24:13.829 --> 24:15.622
His Majesty, my cousin,
the king of England,

24:15.706 --> 24:18.333
strongly suggests we do nothing.

24:21.628 --> 24:24.756
Remember how Prince George
used to enjoy it

24:24.923 --> 24:26.133
when your English mother

24:26.216 --> 24:28.177
and her English doctors would torture you?

24:28.635 --> 24:30.637
George would tease you about your...

24:32.181 --> 24:33.515
deformities.

24:34.433 --> 24:36.268
Yeah, yeah. Yeah.

24:36.435 --> 24:39.354
And don't forget
that sniggering at his side

24:39.521 --> 24:41.356
was your little Russian cousin,

24:42.316 --> 24:43.692
<i>Tsar Nicholas.</i>

24:43.859 --> 24:46.236
Cousin George
is imploring self-restraint

24:46.320 --> 24:49.198
against our other cousin,
the moronic kaiser.

24:49.573 --> 24:52.618
King George has always
protected our interests.

24:52.784 --> 24:55.370
Why would we go to war
over something so trivial?

24:55.537 --> 24:57.497
Because we gave Serbia our word.

24:57.664 --> 24:59.666
And besides, I hate the kaiser.

24:59.958 --> 25:01.793
It will be good
for his oversized ego

25:01.877 --> 25:04.004
to match his undersized hand.

25:04.922 --> 25:06.131
(GIRLS CHUCKLE)

25:06.215 --> 25:08.717
A wise decision, my tsar.

25:09.176 --> 25:12.721
The soul of Russia is safe
in your hands.

25:14.765 --> 25:15.933
ERIK: <i>The world will laugh at you</i>

25:16.016 --> 25:19.770
for not keeping your word
and standing by the Austrians.

25:20.395 --> 25:22.648
Ignore the English king.

25:23.982 --> 25:25.901
Tell George to mind
his own business, <i>ja?</i>

25:26.235 --> 25:27.444
Huh? (LAUGHING)

25:28.820 --> 25:33.700
If I want a war, then I will have it.

25:36.078 --> 25:37.329
As Russia's ally,

25:37.412 --> 25:39.498
we have no choice
but to join this war.

25:39.581 --> 25:41.959
I don't understand.
The kaiser and the tsar

25:42.042 --> 25:44.378
have both ignored
the king's wishes. Why?

25:44.545 --> 25:45.546
That's a good question.

25:45.629 --> 25:47.798
-I...
-With all due respect, sir,

25:47.965 --> 25:49.842
this debate should happen
after we have won the war.

25:50.008 --> 25:51.218
The prime minister is waiting.

25:51.593 --> 25:52.636
And we're late.

25:53.095 --> 25:54.096
Morton's right.

25:54.179 --> 25:57.349
My lord, it would be
my honor to volunteer.

25:58.475 --> 25:59.476
Honor?

25:59.560 --> 26:01.103
KITCHENER: Fine words,
young Conrad.

26:01.520 --> 26:03.021
But therein lies the problem.

26:03.188 --> 26:06.024
Legally, you're not old enough
to join up.

26:06.108 --> 26:08.610
Hmm. But still young enough
to believe

26:08.694 --> 26:11.405
it's an honorable thing
to die for one's country.

26:12.114 --> 26:15.909
The object of war is not
to die for one's country,

26:16.076 --> 26:19.246
but to make the enemy
die for theirs.

26:26.753 --> 26:30.048
COMMANDING SOLDIER:
Fix bayonets!

26:37.055 --> 26:38.140
(WHISTLE BLOWS)

26:38.223 --> 26:40.225
-(SOLDIERS SHOUTING)
-(GUNFIRE)

26:41.351 --> 26:43.353
(SOLDIERS GROANING)

26:48.483 --> 26:50.110
(PANTING)

26:58.076 --> 27:00.037
SHEPHERD: <i>Not even I</i>

27:00.120 --> 27:04.291
<i>could have imagined
a war like this.</i>

27:04.374 --> 27:06.210
(GUNFIRE AND EXPLOSIONS)

27:06.293 --> 27:09.713
<i>What I thought would take
a decade for us to achieve</i>

27:10.964 --> 27:14.968
<i>has taken two short years.</i>

27:19.598 --> 27:23.227
<i>We have drained
Europe's resources</i>

27:23.727 --> 27:27.856
<i>and millions have died pointlessly.</i>

27:28.023 --> 27:29.483
SOLDIER: Fire!

27:29.650 --> 27:31.777
SHEPHERD: <i>We have broken the trust</i>

27:31.860 --> 27:35.656
between the people
and the inbred monarchs

27:35.822 --> 27:39.535
who only rule
due to their fortunate birth.

27:41.328 --> 27:43.789
Do you know who hates King George

27:43.872 --> 27:45.749
more than the kaiser?

27:47.501 --> 27:48.669
Me.

27:49.336 --> 27:51.713
The English monarchy

27:51.880 --> 27:54.758
has oppressed
my beloved Scotland

27:54.842 --> 27:56.635
for over 700 years

27:56.718 --> 28:00.097
and it is time for retribution.

28:00.889 --> 28:04.059
We will pull Russia out of our war

28:04.476 --> 28:07.187
and unleash
the full might of Germany

28:07.271 --> 28:10.357
to destroy England.

28:10.816 --> 28:12.568
Rasputin,

28:12.985 --> 28:17.781
are you ready to begin
the demise of King George?

28:17.948 --> 28:20.576
Thy will be done, my Shepherd.

28:27.291 --> 28:28.667
They've started conscription.

28:28.750 --> 28:30.794
Yes, I'm well aware of that, Conrad.

28:31.545 --> 28:32.546
And?

28:32.754 --> 28:34.089
Well, it was bad enough

28:34.173 --> 28:35.340
I didn't join
when it was voluntary...

28:35.507 --> 28:38.051
Conrad, this is not a war.
Do you understand?

28:38.135 --> 28:39.887
It's not like any war
that we've ever seen.

28:39.970 --> 28:41.805
I don't care! I should be fighting.

28:41.972 --> 28:44.474
It's not fighting. It's dying.

28:46.435 --> 28:48.562
Much like this conversation.

28:51.106 --> 28:52.274
Tell that to Kitchener.

28:58.113 --> 29:00.240
(DOOR OPENS, CLOSES)

29:07.748 --> 29:09.625
OXFORD: You're still too young, Conrad.

29:12.461 --> 29:14.296
CONRAD: But everyone's lying
about their age.

29:14.379 --> 29:16.215
-They're all going over.
-I know.

29:16.965 --> 29:18.342
And I know you want to fight.

29:19.676 --> 29:21.386
It's a testament to your character

29:21.970 --> 29:23.096
and I'm proud of you for it.

29:23.263 --> 29:25.015
Yes, but look what I was given.

29:26.225 --> 29:27.226
In the village.

29:28.727 --> 29:30.270
It's the symbol of a coward.

29:30.687 --> 29:33.023
And I should suffer
such humiliation?

29:34.274 --> 29:37.736
Reputation is
what people think of you.

29:37.903 --> 29:40.489
Character is what you are.

29:46.870 --> 29:48.121
CONRAD: Victoria Cross.

29:49.039 --> 29:50.415
Is it yours?

29:51.250 --> 29:52.251
Yes.

29:53.126 --> 29:54.253
When I was young,

29:54.336 --> 29:57.256
like you, I wanted
to serve my country.

29:58.966 --> 30:00.050
-(GUNFIRE)
-(MEN GROANING)

30:00.133 --> 30:03.011
OXFORD: <i>But soon I began
to question what right we had</i>

30:03.095 --> 30:06.306
to take the land, riches,

30:06.723 --> 30:08.725
and the lives of people

30:08.809 --> 30:11.520
<i>who were only defending
their homeland.</i>

30:14.606 --> 30:16.650
<i>Every man I killed,</i>

30:18.151 --> 30:20.612
<i>I killed a piece of myself.</i>

30:26.994 --> 30:30.414
Maybe having a feather
would have been better.

30:31.999 --> 30:34.793
So, the next day,
I put down my rifle

30:34.877 --> 30:36.086
and I picked up a stretcher.

30:37.212 --> 30:39.381
I should've been given
the Cross for saving lives,

30:39.464 --> 30:40.674
not taking them.

30:43.010 --> 30:45.512
As soon as I replace this
with my own medal,

30:46.847 --> 30:48.432
I'll join the medical corps.

30:51.685 --> 30:53.103
I have informed Kitchener

30:53.187 --> 30:55.063
of your intention of joining up.

30:55.522 --> 30:57.399
And he has assured me
that he will not

30:57.482 --> 30:59.651
let you slip through.

31:40.901 --> 31:43.111
-I have a vision.
-(GROANING SOFTLY)

31:43.612 --> 31:47.032
This boy is the symbol
of the soul of Russia.

31:49.576 --> 31:51.662
You must save Russia.

31:53.580 --> 31:57.918
You must pull out of the war
to save your son's life.

31:58.335 --> 32:00.003
This is nonsense.

32:00.420 --> 32:05.050
You dare to question
the vessel of the Lord?

32:07.594 --> 32:12.182
You dare to risk your son's life?

32:13.433 --> 32:16.645
Nicholas,
come to your senses now!

32:17.187 --> 32:18.689
Please.

32:19.731 --> 32:20.858
Please.

32:28.448 --> 32:30.200
COUSIN FELIX:
<i>My dear cousin Conrad.</i>

32:30.868 --> 32:33.036
<i>It has been too long
since we last saw each other</i>

32:33.203 --> 32:35.497
<i>and I'm sorry I'm only writing
to you now, but...</i>

32:35.581 --> 32:36.957
(CHANTING DEEPLY)

32:37.040 --> 32:38.125
<i>...in these difficult times,</i>

32:38.208 --> 32:39.793
<i>I'm not sure whom I can trust.</i>

32:39.877 --> 32:41.712
(RASPUTIN CONTINUES CHANTING)

32:46.884 --> 32:48.468
Welcome back.

32:50.429 --> 32:52.806
COUSIN FELIX:<i> For a while now,
I've harbored my suspicions</i>

32:52.973 --> 32:55.767
<i>of this so-called priest, Rasputin.</i>

32:56.351 --> 32:58.562
<i>He has the tsar under his spell,</i>

32:58.729 --> 33:01.565
<i>both spiritually
and through opium,</i>

33:03.233 --> 33:06.570
<i>and has persuaded him
to withdraw from the war.</i>

33:08.197 --> 33:10.532
<i>The tsar intends to announce this</i>

33:10.616 --> 33:12.326
<i>in his New Year's speech.</i>

33:12.784 --> 33:14.995
Cousin Felix sends his regards.

33:15.078 --> 33:16.079
Oh.

33:16.330 --> 33:19.291
COUSIN FELIX: <i>I hope your
father's influence can help.</i>

33:20.501 --> 33:23.170
Morton, any ideas?

33:23.670 --> 33:25.964
Well, sir, in my opinion,

33:26.215 --> 33:27.674
this is a very grave situation.

33:27.925 --> 33:29.551
We can trust absolutely no one.

33:29.635 --> 33:31.929
I suggest we assemble
an elite squad of men,

33:32.012 --> 33:34.598
we go to Russia,
and we sort it out ourselves.

33:34.932 --> 33:36.808
Agreed. See to it immediately.

33:36.975 --> 33:41.146
As I'm not allowed to join up,
may I at least go with you?

33:42.814 --> 33:45.567
Conrad, you know your father
made me swear that I would...

33:45.651 --> 33:48.612
Protect my son at all costs.

33:50.489 --> 33:52.658
Where do you want to go, Conrad?

33:54.535 --> 33:55.953
-Russia.
-Why?

33:56.119 --> 33:58.830
To help Cousin Yusupov
deal with Rasputin.

33:58.997 --> 34:00.958
He's going to force Russia
out of the war.

34:01.917 --> 34:03.585
Kitchener, have you killed
so many men

34:03.669 --> 34:04.962
that you're now relying on boys

34:05.045 --> 34:06.129
to run your military intelligence?

34:06.213 --> 34:08.590
-How dare you speak to...
-Shut up, Morton.

34:10.967 --> 34:12.344
Conrad, we're leaving.

34:14.221 --> 34:15.222
Now!

34:26.024 --> 34:27.025
Your lordship?

34:27.568 --> 34:28.652
Let's just hope we don't make

34:28.735 --> 34:30.737
such a mess of things in Russia.

34:40.455 --> 34:42.958
One more dispatch box
for tonight, sir.

34:44.626 --> 34:45.627
Damn it, Morton.

34:45.710 --> 34:47.295
How much do you expect
a man to read?

34:47.462 --> 34:48.589
I'm terribly sorry, my lord.

34:48.672 --> 34:51.257
I would help, but I'm definitely...

34:51.425 --> 34:53.886
definitely more of a soldier
than I am a sailor.

34:54.052 --> 34:56.138
Well, go outside, man,
and get some air.

34:56.972 --> 34:58.140
Quite right.

35:04.062 --> 35:06.064
-(WIND HOWLING)
-(WAVES CRASHING)

35:25.292 --> 35:26.835
(CLOCK TICKING)

35:44.603 --> 35:46.605
(MEN SPEAKING IN GERMAN)

36:02.788 --> 36:04.831
Five million dead.

36:06.542 --> 36:07.960
May God forgive me.

36:30.440 --> 36:32.734
CONRAD: First Ferdinand,
and now Kitchener.

36:32.818 --> 36:34.736
This was not an accident.

36:35.279 --> 36:36.363
Kitchener was your friend.

36:36.780 --> 36:39.074
Not to mention
this country's last hope.

36:39.157 --> 36:40.576
How can you be so calm?

36:40.742 --> 36:42.286
KITCHENER:<i> My dear Oxford.</i>

36:42.452 --> 36:45.330
<i>I wanted to apologize
for our recent fracas.</i>

36:45.706 --> 36:48.750
<i>In my opinion,
Conrad is a fine young man.</i>

36:48.834 --> 36:50.919
He was betrayed.
We must do something.

36:51.378 --> 36:53.046
KITCHENER:<i> Always ready
to face the world.</i>

36:53.213 --> 36:55.549
No, don't ignore me, Father.
You know it's true.

36:55.966 --> 36:57.801
You cannot keep running away
from problems.

36:57.926 --> 37:00.012
KITCHENER:
<i>But I shall, of course,</i>

37:00.095 --> 37:01.388
<i>respect your wishes</i>

37:01.471 --> 37:04.850
<i>and do everything I can
to keep him out of harm's way.</i>

37:04.933 --> 37:06.602
I don't believe
it was a German mine.

37:06.685 --> 37:08.228
There is something more afoot.

37:10.772 --> 37:12.441
And what if you're successful?

37:13.233 --> 37:14.359
What if you're successful

37:14.443 --> 37:15.986
and keep me locked away
as the world burns?

37:16.153 --> 37:18.322
KITCHENER:<i> If all parents
shared your outlook,</i>

37:18.405 --> 37:20.073
<i>there would be no wars.</i>

37:20.616 --> 37:25.871
<i>But until that day comes,
I will no doubt be kept busy.</i>

37:26.496 --> 37:29.249
<i>I remain your friend, Kitch.</i>

37:33.545 --> 37:35.714
Your incessant need to protect me

37:35.881 --> 37:38.425
will not redeem your own failure
to protect Mother.

37:44.389 --> 37:46.308
I'm sorry, Father.

37:54.608 --> 37:56.109
(CHAIR SCRAPES)

37:58.820 --> 37:59.821
No, no.

38:02.783 --> 38:04.034
I'm sorry.

38:08.872 --> 38:09.998
Follow me.

38:44.825 --> 38:47.035
Well, about time.

38:47.578 --> 38:49.121
Welcome to the club.

38:49.872 --> 38:51.498
Is he part of the briefing?

38:51.915 --> 38:53.083
Yes.

38:54.960 --> 38:56.295
Take a look.

39:02.134 --> 39:04.803
You see, this war
has made me realize

39:04.970 --> 39:07.222
that we cannot rely on politicians

39:07.306 --> 39:09.266
to do their job properly.

39:09.600 --> 39:11.810
So, I decided

39:12.436 --> 39:14.396
that we should
do something about it.

39:14.563 --> 39:16.523
This isn't making any sense
to me, Father.

39:16.690 --> 39:17.858
OXFORD: Let me explain.

39:18.150 --> 39:22.321
My reputation is of a man
not wanting to be involved,

39:22.404 --> 39:24.740
which means that my character

39:24.823 --> 39:28.243
finds it much easier
to be involved unnoticed.

39:28.660 --> 39:31.538
Just like domestic servants everywhere

39:31.622 --> 39:33.790
who are seen but not heard.

39:33.874 --> 39:36.043
Essentially invisible.

39:36.710 --> 39:39.588
Unless they're part
of the Oxford family, of course.

39:40.088 --> 39:42.966
Shola and Polly have gathered

39:43.133 --> 39:45.260
a network of domestics

39:45.344 --> 39:47.596
such as the world
has never seen.

39:47.930 --> 39:51.892
While British intelligence
listens at keyholes,

39:53.352 --> 39:56.021
our people
are actually in the room.

39:56.313 --> 39:57.564
-Very clever.
-Hmm.

39:57.773 --> 40:00.234
Now, after Ferdinand's assassination,

40:00.442 --> 40:03.737
I visited Gavrilo Princip
in his prison in Sarajevo.

40:06.532 --> 40:07.783
(GRUNTS)

40:15.457 --> 40:16.542
(GASPING)

40:21.129 --> 40:23.549
-(OXFORD GROANS)
-PRINCIP: Thank you.

40:27.928 --> 40:29.304
Why did you kill my friend?

40:29.680 --> 40:32.558
It was the alcohol.
I was overcome.

40:35.394 --> 40:36.979
I'm just a simple Serb.

40:37.145 --> 40:41.775
A very expensive ring
for such a simple Serb.

40:42.192 --> 40:44.278
Ah, and a secret compartment.

40:44.444 --> 40:47.823
That smelled of almonds.
Therefore, cyanide.

40:48.156 --> 40:51.159
Princip's ring proves
he was not acting alone.

40:51.326 --> 40:54.288
There is, as you say, Conrad,
more afoot.

40:54.454 --> 40:55.455
POLLY: Indeed.

40:57.124 --> 41:00.002
Your cousin's letter made us
extend our network to Russia

41:00.169 --> 41:01.461
and it paid off.

41:02.337 --> 41:05.174
The tsar's nanny found a ring
in Rasputin's chambers.

41:06.842 --> 41:08.844
<i>Identical to Princip's,</i>

41:08.927 --> 41:10.846
but with a tortoise
instead of a bear.

41:11.013 --> 41:13.056
Then I think we must
go to Russia immediately

41:13.140 --> 41:15.809
and find a way
to interrogate this monk.

41:15.976 --> 41:18.520
POLLY: But by all accounts,
Rasputin is unbreakable.

41:19.396 --> 41:21.315
As long as he's alive,

41:21.398 --> 41:22.900
the tsar will never change his mind

41:22.983 --> 41:24.985
and with Russia out of the war,

41:25.527 --> 41:27.237
England is doomed.

41:27.779 --> 41:28.864
SHOLA: My lord.

41:34.036 --> 41:37.164
One life to save millions.

41:42.878 --> 41:43.962
OXFORD: So,

41:44.713 --> 41:47.925
the only way to honor the vow
I made to your mother

41:49.635 --> 41:52.763
is to break the vow
I made to myself.

41:54.348 --> 41:56.642
I'm afraid we have no other choice.

41:58.268 --> 42:02.814
It is time for us
to kill Grigori Rasputin.

42:04.358 --> 42:06.193
(TRAIN HORN BLARING)

42:08.278 --> 42:11.114
Rasputin has accepted
an invitation

42:11.198 --> 42:13.158
to your cousin's Christmas ball.

42:13.659 --> 42:15.452
The tsar's nanny informs me

42:15.536 --> 42:18.956
of Rasputin's weakness
for sweet cakes.

42:19.373 --> 42:22.334
And even sweeter boys.

42:23.377 --> 42:26.463
So, after the main course
is served,

42:27.047 --> 42:30.634
Conrad will entice Rasputin

42:31.134 --> 42:33.637
to a private dessert
in the summer room,

42:34.012 --> 42:37.432
where nanny's legendary
Bakewell tart,

42:37.599 --> 42:39.059
laced with poison,

42:39.810 --> 42:41.019
will be waiting for him.

42:41.186 --> 42:43.230
Polly, get baking.

42:44.231 --> 42:46.400
Yes. And don't forget the poison.

42:52.322 --> 42:54.408
OXFORD: Get him to eat
the cake. Understand?

42:54.575 --> 42:55.576
Yes, Father.

42:55.701 --> 42:58.287
Good.
Tonight we will be rogues,

42:58.912 --> 43:00.330
not Oxfords.

43:03.542 --> 43:05.460
(CANE BANGING)

43:06.170 --> 43:09.965
Our guest of honor,
Father Rasputin.

43:12.009 --> 43:13.844
(DOOR OPENS)

43:55.302 --> 43:57.304
Are you waiters or Englishmen?

43:58.597 --> 44:01.600
Whatever you are,
get me a fucking drink.

44:01.892 --> 44:04.353
Are you a monk or a ballet dancer?

44:10.400 --> 44:13.237
I see you've mastered
the Beryozka glide.

44:13.862 --> 44:17.449
Why don't you glide over there
and get me a fucking drink?

44:24.248 --> 44:26.208
Englishmen.

44:26.500 --> 44:28.168
I like the English.

44:29.962 --> 44:33.090
But it's a long way to come
for a Christmas party.

44:33.423 --> 44:36.218
